qas.question: What happened to Austrian prestige due to the war?

answers.text: Austria's prestige was restored in great part

qas.question: How would Prussia's outcome affect Austria in the long run?

answers.text: was potentially damaging in the long run to Austria's influence in Germany.

qas.question: What area was preserved from Prussian invasion?

answers.text: it did prevent Prussia from invading parts of Saxony
Austria was not able to retake Silesia

qas.question: Who did Frederick II promise to vote for in the imperial elections?

answers.text: by promising to vote for Joseph II in the Imperial elections

context: <a3_0>Austria was not able to retake Silesia<a3_0/> or make any significant territorial gain. However, <a2_0>it did prevent Prussia from invading parts of Saxony<a2_0/>. More significantly, its military performance proved far better than during the War of the Austrian Succession and seemed to vindicate Maria Theresa's administrative and military reforms. Hence, <a0_0>Austria's prestige was restored in great part<a0_0/> and the empire secured its position as a major player in the European system. Also, <a4_0>by promising to vote for Joseph II in the Imperial elections<a4_0/>, Frederick II accepted the Habsburg preeminence in the Holy Roman Empire. The survival of Prussia as a first-rate power and the enhanced prestige of its king and its army, however, <a1_0>was potentially damaging in the long run to Austria's influence in Germany.
